docs.abstract: A new docu-series interviews stars like Oprah Winfrey and Issa Rae to explore the history and shared experiences of Black hair care.
docs.snippet: A new docu-series interviews stars like Oprah Winfrey and Issa Rae to explore the history and shared experiences of Black hair care.
docs.lead_paragraph: When Carri Twigg was a child, her father styled her hair. Every Sunday, he would wash Twigg’s mane in the kitchen sink, and every morning before school he would divide her unruly curls into six, slicked-back braids. The neighborhood knew whenever her father went out of town.

headline.main: ‘The Hair Tales’: Stories of Black Women’s Hair and Self-Acceptance

docs.abstract: Featuring actors mainly performing from their own homes, this multistory drama clumsily wrestles with the struggles of everyday people during the first months of the pandemic.
docs.snippet: Featuring actors mainly performing from their own homes, this multistory drama clumsily wrestles with the struggles of everyday people during the first months of the pandemic.
docs.lead_paragraph: Do you remember the cringey “Imagine” video that Gal Gadot and her league of naïve celebrities devised and posted on social media at the start of the pandemic, in March 2020? “The Same Storm,” written and directed by Peter Hedges (“Dan in Real Life”), and shot using iPhones and laptops around the same time as Gadot’s much-derided lockdown anthem, isn’t all that different. It’s a well-intentioned gesture of solidarity that tries so desperately to be relatable, it feels alienating.

headline.main: ‘The Same Storm’ Review: A Lockdown Grab Bag

docs.abstract: The company continues its fall season with the delight that is “The Dream,” and a Christopher Rudd premiere with an all-Black cast and creative team.
docs.snippet: The company continues its fall season with the delight that is “The Dream,” and a Christopher Rudd premiere with an all-Black cast and creative team.
docs.lead_paragraph: American Ballet Theater had its fall gala on Thursday, celebrating Kevin McKenzie’s final New York season as artistic director. In a preshow talk, he was joined by Susan Jaffe, the company’s incoming artistic director and a former principal. Their attempt at back-and-forth banter — with some bickering thrown in for laughs — was more than a little strange, but eventually they hit on a theme: what it takes to be an artistic director. Hiring dancers and staff, commissioning choreographers, casting, fund-raising — it’s not for the meek.

headline.main: Smoke, Mirrors and Passing the Torch at American Ballet Theater
headline.print_headline: Smoke, Mirrors and Passing the Torch

docs.snippet: Senator Ron Johnson and Lt. Gov. Mandela Barnes put their ideological differences on full display.
docs.lead_paragraph: The first debate between Senator Ron Johnson of Wisconsin, a Republican, and his Democratic challenger, Lt. Gov. Mandela Barnes, was a study in contrasts between an unapologetic, older conservative and a younger liberal who appeared unafraid of his ideological roots.

headline.main: Five Takeaways From the Wisconsin Senate Debate

docs.abstract: Katricia Dotson’s remains were studied, disputed, displayed and litigated. Lost in the controversy was the life of an American girl and her family.
docs.snippet: Katricia Dotson’s remains were studied, disputed, displayed and litigated. Lost in the controversy was the life of an American girl and her family.
docs.lead_paragraph: In early 2019, Janet Monge, then an associate curator at the University of Pennsylvania’s Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology, filmed a class called “Real Bones: Adventures in Forensic Anthropology” for the online education platform Coursera. The goal of the course was to demonstrate how scientists can restore what she called “lost personhood” to the unidentified victims of crimes and natural disasters. “They’ve lost individual identity, so our function is actually to restore parts of that identity,” she explained.

headline.main: She Was Killed by the Police. Why Were Her Bones in a Museum?

docs.abstract: As a result of decades of conversation and scholarship, a wave of new public sculptures reflect and honor Black Britons.
docs.snippet: As a result of decades of conversation and scholarship, a wave of new public sculptures reflect and honor Black Britons.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — At the height of the Black Lives Matter protests in 2020, a statue in Bristol, in the southwest of England was pulled from its plinth, stomped on, graffitied and thrown into the river. Before the incident, Edward Colston, the British slave trader and merchant the sculpture depicted, was a name generally only known by historians.

headline.main: In the U.K., Public Art Shifts Toward Black Experiences

docs.abstract: The entertainer has been widely condemned for a series of antisemitic comments. The fallout across industries has been swift.
docs.snippet: The entertainer has been widely condemned for a series of antisemitic comments. The fallout across industries has been swift.
docs.lead_paragraph: Kanye West has defined most of his career with smash hits and a healthy dose of spectacle and theatrics, helping to redefine the modern concept of celebrity along the way. For a long time, those disruptions were largely welcomed in the music and fashion industries as he cut new creative paths.

headline.main: Kanye West Faces Costly Fallout: A Timeline

docs.abstract: Ensemble Studio Theater’s 38th Marathon of One-Act Plays showcases what can be accomplished in short-form productions, and how, in some cases, they hem ideas in.
docs.snippet: Ensemble Studio Theater’s 38th Marathon of One-Act Plays showcases what can be accomplished in short-form productions, and how, in some cases, they hem ideas in.
docs.lead_paragraph: In Harron Atkins’s multigenerational saga “Still…,” artistic ambitions rub up against personal relationships. Careers wax and wane. A couple forms, bickers, ends — and may or may not be reborn on different terms. We even hear exquisite renditions of “Doo Wop (That Thing)” and “Valerie.”

headline.main: In a Marathon of One-Act Plays, Boundaries Are Pushed and Pulled
headline.print_headline: Offering Up a Bunch of Big Ideas  In Two Programs of Short Plays
